00:02:19.767 --> 00:02:21.367
What is OpenSocial?

00:02:21.367 --> 00:02:24.701
Well, it's essentially a set
of APIs that allow you

00:02:24.701 --> 00:02:26.267
to build social applications.

00:02:26.267 --> 00:02:28.067
And these APIs are standard.

00:02:28.067 --> 00:02:30.567
So what that means is that
it's not one company or,

00:02:30.567 --> 00:02:32.501
you know, one particular
technology.

00:02:32.501 --> 00:02:34.634
These standards have been
brought together

00:02:34.634 --> 00:02:37.968
by a set of companies
that have been collaborating.

00:02:37.968 --> 00:02:39.767
And they've been working,
essentially, since...

00:02:39.767 --> 00:02:42.634
almost, like, two years now.

00:02:42.634 --> 00:02:46.634
So very quickly, what are
the benefits of OpenSocial?

00:02:46.634 --> 00:02:49.200
Well, as you can see here,
before OpenSocial,

00:02:49.200 --> 00:02:51.200
if you wanted to build
an application

00:02:51.200 --> 00:02:52.734
that had social features,

00:02:52.734 --> 00:02:54.267
and you wanted to take
your application

00:02:54.267 --> 00:02:56.367
and put it into
different networks,

00:02:56.367 --> 00:02:57.367
it was a bit of a challenge.

00:02:57.367 --> 00:02:58.767
You really couldn't do that.

00:02:58.767 --> 00:03:02.667
So as you can see here, our
Joe Developer is not too happy.

00:03:02.667 --> 00:03:06.868
But now, with OpenSocial,
that was launched back in 2007,

00:03:06.868 --> 00:03:08.734
there's, essentially,
a set of standards

00:03:08.734 --> 00:03:10.400
for building
social applications.

00:03:10.400 --> 00:03:13.667
And these standards revolve
around three core areas.

00:03:13.667 --> 00:03:16.467
So friends, profiles,
activities.

00:03:16.467 --> 00:03:20.133
And so, basically, once these
standards have been launched,

00:03:20.133 --> 00:03:24.067
this allows for
standardization

00:03:24.067 --> 00:03:25.934
of social application
development

00:03:25.934 --> 00:03:29.434
across any, what we refer to
as container sites,

00:03:29.434 --> 00:03:31.200
